<bill id="DLM3342102" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2010" bill.no="239" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Aquaculture Legislation Amendment Bill (No 3)</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <explnote id="DLM3342103" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" rule-after="yes" rule-before="yes" bill.no="239" bill.type="government" stage="1" year="2010">
      <heading>Explanatory note</heading>
      <explnote.group>
        <heading>General policy statement</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This Bill is an omnibus Bill that implements the Government’s decisions on reforming legislation governing aquaculture. Four separate Acts—the Resource Management Act 1991, the Fisheries Act 1996, the Maori Commercial Aquaculture Claims Settlement Act 2004, and the Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004—will be amended by the Bill. It is intended that the Bill will be divided into 4 separate bills during the committee of the whole House stage of the legislative process.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This Bill incorporates provisions in the Aquaculture Legislation Amendment Bill (No 2) as reported by the Primary Production Select Committee in September 2009, where those provisions remain relevant in the context of this Bill.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The current law is constraining the aquaculture industry’s growth; no new aquaculture space has been created under the current (2004) regime. This Bill’s purpose is to provide an efficient legislative and regulatory framework that enables the sustainable development of aquaculture within the coastal marine area. The Bill is part of a wider programme of reform that includes non-regulatory measures to provide for a more active role for the Government in the development and management of aquaculture.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Streamlining planning and consenting processes</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The current law provides that aquaculture activities can take place only within aquaculture management areas identified in regional coastal plans. This regime has not worked well because of its complexity and poor incentives for councils and industry to plan for and invest in aquaculture. The Bill removes the requirement for aquaculture management areas. This change normalises aquaculture within the Resource Management Act framework by enabling applicants to apply directly for a resource consent in any part of the coastal marine area, subject to the provisions of the relevant regional coastal plan.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill makes changes to streamline planning and consenting processes, reduce costs to industry, and provide stronger incentives for industry development, while maintaining existing processes for ensuring environmental limits are respected.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Investment certainty will be enhanced. The Bill contains measures to provide a minimum 20-year term for aquaculture consents (except where the applicant requests a shorter term or there is significant uncertainty about the effects of the proposal that cannot otherwise be adequately managed). The consenting process for continuation of an existing aquaculture activity will be simplified by limiting the information applicants must provide to councils.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill empowers the Minister of Conservation to approve, by <emphasis style="italic">Gazette</emphasis> notice, the use of an allocation tool by a regional council for managing high or competing demand. This measure will enable councils to more readily apply alternatives to <quote.in quote="1">first in, first served</quote.in> to manage demand for space in the coastal marine area. In addition, councils will be able to request the Minister of Aquaculture to direct the suspension of new aquaculture applications for a period of up to 1 year where the provisions in a regional coastal plan are inadequate for dealing with demand for coastal space in that region. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Accreditation requirements for members of hearings panels will be extended to improve the robustness of decisions, including but not limited to decisions on aquaculture matters.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Streamlining undue adverse effects on fishing test</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill retains the Fisheries Act requirement for an aquaculture decision. This requires the Ministry of Fisheries to assess whether a proposed aquaculture activity will have undue adverse effects on commercial, customary, or recreational fishing (the <emphasis style="bold">UAE test</emphasis>). The Bill makes changes to streamline the application process, simplify information requirements, and better integrate the UAE test with Resource Management Act consent processes. The right of appeal to the High Court for UAE decisions is removed; UAE decisions will be subject to judicial review only. The Bill retains the underlying approach of ensuring fishing quota holders (commercial fishers) are fairly compensated for any undue adverse effects of aquaculture development on fishing, but makes changes to the process for negotiating voluntary aquaculture agreements. The Bill allows aquaculture applicants to negotiate an aquaculture agreement with fishing quota holders and register it before the UAE test is undertaken, in which case a UAE assessment in respect of commercial fishing will not be carried out for the relevant stocks. The Bill lowers the required consent threshold for aquaculture agreements to 75% of quota.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Government leadership</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill enables the Government to take a more active role in aquaculture planning and consenting. The Minister of Aquaculture will be empowered to recommend the making of regulations amending provisions in regional coastal plans relating to the management of aquaculture activities in the coastal marine area.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Changes to regional coastal plans</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill will make changes to regional coastal plans in regions where current plan provisions present the greatest barriers to aquaculture growth or the opportunities are greatest. Those changes will enable applications to be made for the farming of a wider range of species, including finfish, and some expansion of existing farms.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Transitioning existing farms, outstanding applications and interim aquaculture management areas</explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill contains a range of measures to bring existing marine farms into the new regime with minimal disturbance, and to enable the processing of outstanding applications including those <quote.in quote="1">frozen</quote.in> under the current law. In most cases, the Bill will allow processing of those applications to proceed on commencement of the new law, subject to the provisions of the relevant regional coastal plan. The scope of the UAE test for applications lodged before the 2001 aquaculture moratorium will be narrowed to align it with the current law. The 2 interim aquaculture management areas (in Tasman and Waikato) will be concluded under the current law, since both are at a late stage in the process. This will include the allocation of settlement space in accordance with the Maori Commercial Aquaculture Claims Settlement Act 2004.</text>
        </para>
        <explnote.crosshead>Delivering the Maori Commercial Aquaculture Claims Settlement </explnote.crosshead>
        <para>
          <text>The Maori Commercial Aquaculture Claims Settlement Act 2004 provides for the full and final settlement of contemporary Maori claims to commercial aquaculture space in the coastal marine area, and for the transfer, allocation, and management of aquaculture settlement assets.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>A new mechanism for delivering the Crown's obligations in respect of new space is, however, needed as a consequence of removing the requirement that aquaculture activities must be located within aquaculture management areas.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Bill retains the core components of the aquaculture settlement, including all rights associated with 20% of new space created for aquaculture from 1 January 2005. The Bill is focussed on ensuring that the Crown's obligations under the settlement are maintained under the new regime by essentially retaining the mechanism already in place under the Maori Commercial Aquaculture Claims Settlement Act 2004.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Pending development of an alternative mechanism that might better fit the new aquaculture regime, the Bill’s current formulation of the mechanism delivers on the Crown's obligations.</text>
        </para>
      </explnote.group>
