      <explnote.group>
        <heading>Clause by clause analysis</heading>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 1</emphasis> is the Title clause.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <clause.desc>
          <para>
            <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 2</emphasis> is the commencement clause. <emphasis style="italic">Clause 69(3)</emphasis> comes into force 2 years after the date on which the Bill receives the Royal assent. The rest of the Bill comes into force on 1 July 2011.</text>
          </para>
        </clause.desc>
        <explnote.part id="DLM3342104">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">1  </label>
          <heading>Amendments to Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004</heading>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 3</emphasis> provides that this Part amends the Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 4</emphasis> amends section 3, which states the purpose of the Act. The amendment adds a new provision to refer to the amendments made by this Bill.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 5</emphasis> amends section 4, which explains how the Act is arranged. The amendments include general references to the reforms made by this Bill and repeal the provisions relating to the table of situations and relevant provisions.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 6</emphasis> amends section 10, which provides for certain leases and licences under the Marine Farming Act 1971 to be deemed coastal permits.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>The amendments—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>clarify when leases and licences that are subject to discontinued forfeiture become deemed coastal permits:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provide that the 12-month period for reviewing conditions of deemed coastal permits starts from when a lease or licence is deemed to be a coastal permit:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>clarify the rights of objection against decisions about the review of conditions.</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 7</emphasis> amends section 17(2). The amendment is a consequential amendment arising from the amendments made by <emphasis style="italic">clause 6</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 8</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new sections 17A and 17B</emphasis>. <emphasis style="italic">New section 17A</emphasis> extends the terms of certain marine farming leases in the coastal marine area in the Waikare Inlet in the Bay of Islands. <emphasis style="italic">New section 17B</emphasis> deems the Coromandel Marine Farmers Association Incorporated to have been granted resource consents to undertake marine farming in the Waikato Communal Area.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 9</emphasis> amends section 20, which provides for certain marine farming permits under section 67J of the Fisheries Act 1983 to be deemed coastal permits. The amendments—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>provide that the 12-month period for reviewing conditions of deemed coastal permits starts from when a permit is deemed to be a coastal permit:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>clarify the rights of objection against decisions about the review of conditions.</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 10</emphasis> amends section 21, which provides for certain spat catching permits under section 67Q(2) of the Fisheries Act 1983 to be deemed coastal permits. The amendments parallel those made by <emphasis style="italic">clause 9</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 11</emphasis> repeals section 24. This is a consequential amendment arising from the amendments made by <emphasis style="italic">clauses 9 and 10</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 12</emphasis> amends section 25, which provides for certain applications under the Fisheries Act 1983 to be determined under that Act as if the Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004 had not been passed. The amendments clarify the application of the 2004 Act and make section 25 subject to <emphasis style="italic">new section 25A</emphasis> inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 13</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 13</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new sections 25A and 25B</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 25A</emphasis> applies to applications that section 25(1) applies to and that have not been determined as at the commencement of this Part of the Bill. The purpose of the new section is to defer an application being declined if the application does not meet the <amend.in quote="1">undue adverse effects</amend.in> test, but only in relation to commercial fishing. In such a case, a 6-month period is provided for the lodgement of an aquaculture agreement. If an aquaculture agreement is lodged within that time, the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries may grant the application.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 25B</emphasis> contains supplementary provisions for the purpose of <emphasis style="italic">new section 25A</emphasis> relating to obtaining further information and rights of appeal or objection.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 14</emphasis> amends section 26, which provides when applications for marine farming and spat catching permits can be made after the commencement of the Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004. The amendments—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>clarify the application of the 2004 Act:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>insert a new provision making the application of the 2004 Act subject to <emphasis style="italic">new section 26A</emphasis> inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 15</emphasis>:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>places limitations on applications by persons who made applications before the 2004 Act that were declined.</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 15</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new sections 26A and 26B</emphasis>, which relate to applications to which section 26 applies and which contain provisions that parallel those in <emphasis style="italic">new sections 25A and 25B</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 16</emphasis> amends section 27, which provides for the order in which certain applications and requests are to be processed. The amendments omit references to aquaculture management areas and include a reference to requests for aquaculture decisions under section 37.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 17</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 29.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 18</emphasis> inserts new definitions in section 35.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 19</emphasis> makes a technical drafting amendment to section 37(2).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 20</emphasis> substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new section 44</emphasis>, which recasts the current section to take account of <emphasis style="italic">new sections 44A to 44N</emphasis> as inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 21</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 21</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new sections 44A to 44N</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 44A</emphasis> provides an overview of <emphasis style="italic">new sections 44B to 44L</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>The purpose of <emphasis style="italic">new sections 44B to 44L</emphasis> is to provide a process for allocation to Te Ohu Kaimoana Trustee Limited of authorisations in respect of 20% of any space in an interim aquaculture management area in respect of which the chief executive has made a determination or a reservation relating to commercial fishing.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 44B to 44D</emphasis> provide a negotiating period for the persons specified in <emphasis style="italic">new section 44B(2)</emphasis> to try to reach an agreement about the allocation of authorisations in respect of the space.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 44E to 44H</emphasis> provide a process for allocation of authorisations in respect of the space, if the persons specified in <emphasis style="italic">new section 44B(2)</emphasis> have failed to reach agreement.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 44E to 44H</emphasis> apply only to the extent that an agreement is not entered into by the persons specified in <emphasis style="italic">new section 44B(2)</emphasis> within the required period. These new sections provide how a regional council, in the absence of agreement, is to allocate authorisations to the trustee.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 44I</emphasis> limits who may apply for a coastal permit to occupy agreed space or identified space that is subject to a reservation in relation to commercial fishing to persons who hold an authorisation for the space and an aquaculture agreement.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 44J</emphasis> provides when an iwi aquaculture organisation may lodge an aquaculture agreement if the trustee has not been authorised to enter into an aquaculture agreement.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 44K</emphasis> provides when the trustee may lodge an aquaculture agreement if the trustee has been authorised to enter into an aquaculture agreement.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 44L</emphasis> disapplies <emphasis style="italic">new section 165R</emphasis> of the Resource Management Act 1991 and substitutes different rules about whether and to what extent authorisations allocated under the Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004 lapse.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 44M</emphasis> deems areas that became aquaculture management areas under section 44 to be <emphasis style="italic">Gazetted</emphasis> aquaculture areas.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 44N</emphasis> contains further provisions about <emphasis style="italic">Gazetted</emphasis> aquaculture areas.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 22</emphasis> substitutes a <emphasis style="italic">new section 45</emphasis> that provides that deemed aquaculture management areas cease to exist after the commencement of <emphasis style="italic">Part 3</emphasis> of the Bill.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 23</emphasis> substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new sections 47 to 47B</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 47</emphasis> clarifies the process of resuming the processing of applications after the end of the moratorium on 31 December 2004. Applications are to be processed in the order they were received, but where they relate to an interim aquaculture management area, only if the chief executive has made a determination or reservation in relation to commercial fishing and the consenting authority has completed the allocation of authorisations to the trustee in the area concerned.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 47A</emphasis> applies to applications for coastal permits for aquaculture activities made on or after 1 January 2005 but before 10 May 2006. This section contains similar provisions to <emphasis style="italic">new section 47</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 47B</emphasis> contains further provisions about processing the applications that <emphasis style="italic">new sections 47 and 47A</emphasis> apply to.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 24</emphasis> amends section 48. This is a technical drafting amendment.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 25</emphasis> repeals section 49(1)(b) to remove a redundant reference to an aquaculture management area.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 26</emphasis> amends section 50 to make it subject to <emphasis style="italic">new section 50A</emphasis> inserted by the next clause.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 27</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new sections 50A and 50B</emphasis>, which relate to certain applications referred to in section 50(3). The new sections contain provisions that parallel those in <emphasis style="italic">new sections 25A, 25B, 26A, and 26B</emphasis>, inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clauses 13 and 15</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 28</emphasis> amends section 53, which provides for applications to amend deemed coastal permits to reflect the actual space they occupied. The amendments extend the period for making applications for 12 months after the Bill is passed and make technical changes to the appeal rights against decisions on application.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 29</emphasis> substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new section 56</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 30</emphasis> adds <emphasis style="italic">new Schedules 1 and 2</emphasis> to the principal Act. <emphasis style="italic">New Schedule 1</emphasis> contains the conditions of marine farming permit 364 referred to in <emphasis style="italic">new section 17B</emphasis> inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 8</emphasis>. <emphasis style="italic">New Schedule 2</emphasis> contains additional provisions relating to aquaculture agreements for the purposes of <emphasis style="italic">new sections 25A, 26A, and 50A</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM3342105">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">2  </label>
          <heading>Amendments to Fisheries Act 1996</heading>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 31</emphasis> provides that this Part amends the Fisheries Act 1996.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 32</emphasis> amends section 2, which defines terms used in the Fisheries Act 1996. The amendments omit the definition of <emphasis style="bold">aquaculture management area</emphasis> and insert a definition of <emphasis style="bold">regional council</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 33</emphasis> amends section 6, which addresses the relationship between regional plans and coastal permits under the Resource Management Act 1991 and the Fisheries Act 1996. The amendments are consequential on abolishing aquaculture management areas.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 34</emphasis> amends section 186C, which defines terms used in Part 9A, which relates to aquaculture. The amendments recast definitions consequential on abolishing aquaculture management areas.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 35</emphasis> substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new sections 186D to 186GA</emphasis>, which relate to the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries making aquaculture decisions and obtaining information for the purpose of making aquaculture decisions. These sections have been recast to take account of the abolition of aquaculture management areas and of the new process whereby the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries receives a request for an aquaculture decision from a regional council in relation to the grant of a coastal permit authorising aquaculture activities in the coastal marine area.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 36</emphasis> amends section 186H, which specifies the requirements for an aquaculture decision. The amendment recasts the provisions about revoking or amending rules in a regional coastal plan without a further aquaculture decision so that the provisions apply instead to conditions in coastal permits.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 37</emphasis> repeals section 186I, which provides for appeals to the High Court against aquaculture decisions.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 38</emphasis> amends section 186J, which provides a time limit within which judicial review must be sought of an aquaculture decision. The time limit is shortened from 3 months to 15 working days after the notification of the aquaculture decision.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 39</emphasis> substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new section 186ZD</emphasis>, which defines terms used in subpart 4 of Part 9A. The new section carries forward the existing definition of <emphasis style="bold">aquaculture agreement</emphasis> and inserts a new definition of <emphasis style="bold">pre-request aquaculture agreement</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 40</emphasis> amends section 186ZE, which requires a register of aquaculture agreements to be kept. The amendments require a register of pre-request aquaculture agreements to be kept.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 41</emphasis> substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new section 186ZF</emphasis>, which specifies the fishers whose consent is necessary for an aquaculture agreement. The current level of registered quota owners of the stock concerned holding not less than 90% of quota shares for the stock is reduced to 75%.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 42</emphasis> makes amendments to section 186ZG that are consequential on the amendments made by <emphasis style="italic">clause 41</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 43</emphasis> amends section 186ZI, which provides when aquaculture agreements are to be lodged for registration. The amendments insert reference to a prescribed fee and specify a time limit of 6 months after public notice of a reservation under section 186H(3).</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 44</emphasis> amends section 186ZJ, which provides that no proceedings may be brought against decisions of the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries in relation to the lodging of aquaculture agreements. The amendment adds a reference to <emphasis style="italic">new section 186ZM</emphasis> inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 46</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 45</emphasis> amends section 186ZL, which provides for a memorial to be recorded in the appropriate register if the chief executive makes a reservation. The amendments arise from the abolition of aquaculture management areas.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 46</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new section 186ZM</emphasis>, which provides for the registration of pre-request aquaculture agreements. These are agreements made before a regional council requests the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries to make an aquaculture decision.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 47</emphasis> amends section 297, which authorises the making of regulations. The amendment inserts a new paragraph providing for fees and charges in respect of the chief executive functions in relation to aquaculture activities.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 48</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 305B.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM3342106">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">3  </label>
          <heading>Amendments to Maori Commercial Aquaculture Claims Settlement Act 2004</heading>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 49</emphasis> provides that this Part amends the Maori Commercial Aquaculture Claims Settlement Act 2004.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 50</emphasis> amends section 4, which defines terms used in the Act. The amendments repeal the definition of <emphasis style="bold">aquaculture management area</emphasis> and substitute a new definition of <emphasis style="bold">new space</emphasis>, being space that, after the commencement of this Part of the Bill, first becomes subject to a coastal permit authorising aquaculture activities.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 51</emphasis> amends section 5, which defines <emphasis style="bold">settlement assets</emphasis>. The amendment includes authorisations relating to aquaculture activities under the Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 52</emphasis> amends the heading above section 7.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 53</emphasis> repeals sections 7 to 16 and substitutes <emphasis style="italic">new sections 7 to 7D</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 7A</emphasis> imposes a general obligation on the Crown to deliver to Maori the settlement of Maori claims to commercial aquaculture. The Crown can comply with the obligation by ensuring that 20% of new space in the coastal marine area is transferred to the trustee for the purpose of aquaculture activities or by agreeing to an equivalent by way of a regional agreement.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 7B</emphasis> authorises the Crown to acquire or purchase authorisations or coastal permits for the purpose of complying with <emphasis style="italic">new section 7A</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 7C and 7D</emphasis> apply sections 29 and 29A for the purposes of <emphasis style="italic">new section 7A</emphasis>. Those sections relate to the purchase of coastal permits and to regional agreements in relation to pre-commencement space in the coastal marine area.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 54</emphasis> amends section 17(2) to substitute a reference to <emphasis style="italic">section 44</emphasis> of the Aquaculture Reform (Repeals and Transitional Provisions) Act 2004, which requires a regional council to comply with <emphasis style="italic">new sections 44A to 44E</emphasis> of that Act.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 55</emphasis> repeals section 22(3)(a), which is consequential on the repeal of section 25 by <emphasis style="italic">clause 56</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 56 and 57</emphasis> repeal sections 25 and 26 respectively.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 58</emphasis> amends section 45(4), which deals with the trustee determining settlement assets allocation entitlements only on the basis of a written agreement of all iwi aquaculture organisations. The amendment relates to the 12-month period specified in the provision so that the period runs from the recognition of all organisations and the allocation of the first of the settlement assets.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 59</emphasis> amends section 47 to substitute <emphasis style="italic">new subsection (1)</emphasis> so that an allocation of settlement assets in accordance with Schedule 1 may be done at the end of the 12-month period specified in <emphasis style="italic">section 45(4A)</emphasis> if an iwi aquaculture organisation notifies the trustee that it does not intend to enter into a written agreement.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
        <explnote.part id="DLM3342107">
          <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes">4  </label>
          <heading>Amendments to Resource Management Act 1991</heading>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 60</emphasis> provides that this Part amends the Resource Management Act 1991.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 61</emphasis> amends section 2(1), which defines terms used in Act. The amendments—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>clarify that all activities described in section 12 come within the definition of <emphasis style="bold">aquaculture activities</emphasis> if done for the purpose of the activities specified in paragraph (a) of the definition:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>exclude from the definition of <emphasis style="bold">aquaculture activities</emphasis> any activity carried out solely for the purpose of monitoring the environment:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>repeal the definition of <emphasis style="bold">aquaculture management area</emphasis>.</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 62 and 63</emphasis> repeal sections 12A and 12B respectively.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 64</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 28, which specifies the functions of the Minister of Conservation.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 65</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new section 28B</emphasis>, which specifies the functions of the Minister of Aquaculture.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 66</emphasis> amends section 30, which specifies the functions of regional councils. The amendments substitute <emphasis style="italic">new subsections (2) and (3)</emphasis> to clarify that a regional council and the Minister of Conservation cannot perform their functions to manage fishing or fisheries resources, but can perform their functions to avoid, remedy, or mitigate the effects of aquaculture activities on fishing and fisheries resources.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 67</emphasis> amends section 32, which requires certain Ministers and other persons to carry out an evaluation in respect of certain functions. The amendment adds a reference to the Minister of Aquaculture for regulations made under <emphasis style="italic">new section 360A</emphasis> as inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 96</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 68</emphasis> amends section 36AA, which requires a local authority to provide a discount on administrative charges. The amendment substitutes a <emphasis style="italic">new subsection (1)</emphasis>, which requires a local authority to provide a discount in accordance with—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>regulations made under section 360(1)(hj); or</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>any policy adopted under section 36AA, if the policy is more generous than that provided by the regulations.</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 69</emphasis> amends section 39B, which provides for when a local authority may authorise a person or group to conduct hearings. The amendments—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>include reference to a plan change notified under clause 5 of Schedule 1:</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>recast the circumstances in which a local authority may authorise a group of persons to conduct hearings. (This amendment comes into force 2 years after the Bill receives the Royal assent.)</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 70</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 64 consequential on the repeal of Schedule 1A by <emphasis style="italic">clause 99</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 71</emphasis> makes a consequential drafting amendment to section 67.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 72</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new section 68A</emphasis>, which provides that, after the commencement of this Part of the Bill, no rule may be included in a regional coastal plan which authorises as a permitted activity any aquaculture activity in the coastal marine area. Transitional provisions apply for regional coastal plans that contain such a rule at the commencement of this Part of the Bill.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 73</emphasis> amends section 86B, which provides for when rules in proposed plans and changes have legal effect. The amendments recast provisions to take account of the abolition of aquaculture management areas.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 74</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 87A.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 75</emphasis> amends section 88, which deals with making applications for resource consents. The amendments relate to applications for coastal permits to undertake aquaculture activities. An application must include a copy for the Ministry of Fisheries. If an application is for a coastal permit that section 165ZH(1)(a)(ii) applies to, the assessment required by section 88(2) relates only to information that the effects of the activity are no longer the same or similar in character, intensity, or scale to those anticipated at the time the original consent was granted.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 76</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 104 that is consequential on the repeal of section 107E by <emphasis style="italic">clause 78</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 77 and 78</emphasis> repeal the heading above section 107E and section 107E respectively.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 79</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new section 107F</emphasis>, which requires a consent authority to provide certain information to the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries in relation to an application for a coastal permit authorising aquaculture activities to be undertaken in the coastal marine area.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 80</emphasis> amends section 114, which requires a consent authority to notify its decision on an application for a resource consent. The amendments add provisions that require additional notification to the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries and advice to the applicant that the decision is still subject to an aquaculture decision.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 81</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 116 consequential on <emphasis style="italic">new section 116A</emphasis> as inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 82</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 82</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new section 116A</emphasis>, which provides for when a coastal permit for aquaculture activities commences. The general approach is that the effect of the coastal permit is deferred while the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries makes an aquaculture decision. Depending on the decision made, the permit proceeds, is amended, deferred pending registration of an aquaculture agreement, or cancelled.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 83</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment consequential on <emphasis style="italic">new section 123A</emphasis> as inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 84</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 84</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new section 123A</emphasis>, which provides for the duration of coastal permits authorising aquaculture activities. The period stated in a coastal period must not be shorter than 20 years or longer than 35 years. In certain circumstances, a period shorter than 20 years can be specified.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 85</emphasis> amends section 125, which deals with the lapsing of resource consents. A shorter period of 3 years is provided for the lapsing of a resource consent authorising aquaculture activities to be undertaken in the coastal marine area.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 86</emphasis> amends section 127, which deals with the change or cancellation of the conditions of a resource consent on application of the holder of the consent. The amendment adds <emphasis style="italic">new subsection (3A)</emphasis>, which clarifies that the change or cancellation of a condition of a coastal permit authorising aquaculture activities does not require an aquaculture decision unless the condition has been specified under section 186H of the Fisheries Act 1996 as requiring an aquaculture decision.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 87</emphasis> amends section 128, which deals with the circumstances when a consent authority may review conditions of a resource consent. The amendment requires a regional council to notify the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries if it intends to review a condition of a coastal permit that has been specified under section 186H of the Fisheries Act 1996 as a condition that needs an aquaculture decision before it is changed.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 88</emphasis> amends section 132, which deals with the decisions of a consent authority reviewing the conditions of a resource consent. The amendment applies <emphasis style="italic">new sections 114(4) and 116A</emphasis> (as inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clauses 80 and 82</emphasis> respectively) if a regional council intends to change a condition of a coastal permit in relation to which the council is required to notify the chief executive of the Ministry of Fisheries.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 89</emphasis> makes drafting amendments to section 149N consequential on the abolition of aquaculture management areas.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 90</emphasis> repeals subpart 1 of Part 7A and substitutes a <emphasis style="italic">new subpart 1</emphasis>, comprising <emphasis style="italic">new sections 165A to 165ZA</emphasis>, dealing with managing occupation in the coastal marine area.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text>Complete replacement of subpart 1 means that some provisions in the current subpart are carried forward with little or no change and do not indicate any change in policy.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 165A</emphasis> defines terms used in the new subpart.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 165B</emphasis> permits a consent authority to refuse an application for a coastal permit if the consent authority has, within the previous 1 year, refused the same or similar application.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New section 165C</emphasis> requires a consent authority to cancel an application for a coastal permit authorising occupation of the coastal marine area for aquaculture activities if the application is made after 9 May 2006, but before the commencement of the Resource Management Amendment Act 2008.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 165D to 165I</emphasis> deal with provisions in regional coastal plans relating to occupation of the coastal marine area. A regional coastal plan may include provisions to address the effects of occupation and to manage competition for occupation of space (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165D</emphasis>). A regional coastal plan may provide for a method of allocating authorisations for space vested in the Crown or a regional council (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165E</emphasis>). Before adopting a method for allocating authorisations, a regional council must have regard to, and be satisfied about certain matters (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165F</emphasis>). If a regional coastal plan provides or requires a method of allocating authorisations, a regional council may or must (as the case may require) offer authorisations by public notice (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165G</emphasis>). If a regional coastal plan provides for the allocation of authorisations of space by public tender or another method, a person must not be granted a coastal permit unless the person holds an authorisation for the space (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165H</emphasis>). An Order in Council may be made on the recommendation of the Minister of Conservation directing a regional council not to proceed with a proposed allocation of authorisations or to proceed with a proposed allocation to give effect to the matters specified in the order (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165I</emphasis>)</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 165J to 165O</emphasis> provide for ministerial approval of use of methods of allocating authorisations. A regional council may request the Minister of Conservation to approve an allocation method for authorisations if the regional coastal plan does not provide or does not provide effectively for actual or anticipated high demand or competition for coastal permits for occupation of space in the coastal marine area (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165J</emphasis>). If a regional council has made a request, a person may not apply for a coastal permit to occupy space that is subject to the request until the request has been declined or approval of an allocation method is notified in the <emphasis style="italic">Gazette</emphasis> (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165K</emphasis>). The process for the Minister of Conservation to deal with requests is set out in <emphasis style="italic">new section 165L</emphasis>. The period of any approval, the power to revoke an approval, and the power to substitute an approval are set out in <emphasis style="italic">new section 165M</emphasis>. If approval is given to an allocation method, the regional council must by public notice offer authorisations in accordance with the approval (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165N</emphasis>). While an approval is in force no person may apply for a coastal permit authorising occupation of the coastal marine area for the purpose of aquaculture activities unless the person holds an authorisation (<emphasis style="italic">new section 165O</emphasis>).</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 165P to 165Y</emphasis> deal with a range of miscellaneous matters relating to authorisations and carry forward a number of provisions with little or no amendment, such as the current sections 165L, 165M, 165P, 165Q, 165R, 165S, 165T, 165U, and 165V.</text>
            </para>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">New sections 165Z and 165ZA</emphasis> contain new powers exercisable by the Minister of Aquaculture—</text>
              <list>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>to suspend the receipt of applications for coastal permits to occupy the coastal marine area for the purpose of aquaculture activities; or</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                  <para>
                    <text>to direct that such applications be processed and heard together.</text>
                  </para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 91</emphasis> repeals subpart 2 of Part 7A.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 92</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 165ZG that is consequential on the abolition of aquaculture management areas.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 93</emphasis> makes a number of drafting amendments, including an amendment consequential on <emphasis style="italic">new section 17B</emphasis> inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 8</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 94</emphasis> amends section 165ZJ, which provides additional criteria for considering applications for permits already used for aquaculture activities. The amendment repeals subsection (1)(c), which refers to the use of current industry good practice for any current aquaculture activities.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 95</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to section 357A, which is consequential on the amendment made to section 125 by <emphasis style="italic">clause 85</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 96</emphasis> inserts <emphasis style="italic">new sections 360A to 360C</emphasis>, which authorise the making of regulations that amend the provisions of a regional coastal plan that relate to the management of aquaculture activities in the coastal marine area.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 97</emphasis> amends section 401A, which provides for transitional coastal occupation charges. The amendments omit references to specific dates and substitute references to <quote.in quote="1">expiry date</quote.in>, which is defined to mean the date that is 3 years after the commencement of this clause.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 98</emphasis> makes a drafting amendment to clause 25(4)(b) of Schedule 1 that is consequential on <emphasis style="italic">new section 360A</emphasis> inserted by <emphasis style="italic">clause 96</emphasis>.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clause 99</emphasis> repeals Schedule 1A.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
          <clause.desc>
            <para>
              <text><emphasis style="italic">Clauses 100 and 101</emphasis> amend the proposed Tasman regional coastal plan and the Waikato regional coastal plan respectively. The amendments are set out in <emphasis style="italic">Schedules 2 and 3</emphasis> respectively.</text>
            </para>
          </clause.desc>
        </explnote.part>
      </explnote.group>
    </explnote>
  </billdetail>
